		<div class="body">
            
			<h2>
                
                Using a Linux laptop in text mode
			</h2>
            

            
            <div class="precis">Linux has everything you need to use your laptop even if you choose not to use the pointy-clicky interfaces</div>
            

            <p>So having recently got a <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160526225625/http://www.uncarved.com/blog/netbook.mrk" title="In which I talk about my netbook">netbook</a>, I have been learning how to do everything on it.  It's obviously all easy if you use something like <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160526225625/http://www.xfce.org/" title="XFCE - A lightweight Linux desktop">xfce</a> or <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160526225625/http://www.gnome.org/" title="gnome - the standard desktop for Fedora Linux">gnome</a>, or some netbook-specific spin like the <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160526225625/http://www.ubuntu.com/GetUbuntu/download-netbook" title="A powerful, yet friendly netbook-specific Linux variant">Ubuntu netbook remix</a>, but I like to use <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20160526225625/http://xmonad.org/" title="xmonad - A lightweight x window manager">xmonad</a>, so it helps to learn how to do all the laptoppy things in text mode.</p>
<p>Here's a list of things it's useful to know:</p>
<ul>
<li>nm-applet - finds a network and connects to it automagically</li>
<li>pm-suspend - sends your laptop into a light sleep</li>
<li>pm-hibernate - sends your laptop into a heavy sleep where it uses no battery</li>
</ul>
